definition.value: A penicillin in which the substituent at position 6 of the penam ring is a phenylacetamido group.
The parent compound of the citrulline class consisting of ornithine having a carbamoyl group at the N(5)-position.
An aldopentose, found in the embryos of most edible plants and used in medicine to test for malabsorption by administration in water to the patient.
A diazaalkane consisting of octane having the two aza groups at the 3- and 6-positions.
A galactosamine phosphate that is D-galactosamine substituted at position 1 by a monophosphate group.
An alpha-amino acid that is glutaric acid bearing a single amino substituent at position 2.
The L-stereoisomer of 4-hydroxyproline.
A 2'-deoxyribonucleoside monophosphate compound with the phosphate group in the 5'-position.
A beta-D-glucan in which the glucose units are connected by (1->4) linkages.
An iron group element atom that has atomic number 26.
A chondroitin sulfate in which the site of sulfation is carbon 4 of the N-acetylgalactosamine (GalNAc) sugar.
Any nucleoside where the sugar component is D-ribose.
An alpha-amino acid that is pentanoic acid bearing two amino substituents at positions 2 and 5.
A medium-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of dodecanoic acid (lauric acid); major species at pH 7.3.
An elemental molecule consisting of two hydrogens joined by a single bond.
That part of DNA or RNA that may be involved in pairing.
Any form of fucose having L configuration.
An  organic chloride salt of thiamine(1+) diphosphate.
A chondroitin sulfate in which the site of sulfation is carbon 6 of the N-acetylgalactosamine (GalNAc) sugar.
A butenedioic acid in which the double bond has cis- (Z)-configuration.
A class of aminophospholipids in which a phosphatidyl group is esterified to the hydroxy group of serine.
A monosaccharide derivative that is  hydroquinone attached to a beta-D-glucopyranosyl residue at position 4 via a glycosidic linkage.
A alpha,beta-unsaturated monocarboxylic acid that is ethene substituted by a carboxy group.
An acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbon having the general formula CnH2n+2, and therefore consisting entirely of hydrogen atoms and saturated carbon atoms.
The threo-diastereomer of 1,4-dimercaptobutane-2,3-diol.
A myo-inositol monophosphate derivative that is 1D-myo-inositol substituted at position 1 by an sn-glycero-3-phospho group.
A keratan sulfate with random sulfation at the 6'-position.
The D-enantiomer of arabinitol.
A purine ribonucleoside 5'-tetraphosphate having adenine as the nucleobase.
A vitamin B6 phosphate that is the  phosphoric ester derivative of pyridoxamine.
A member of the class of benzaldehydes carrying methoxy and hydroxy substituents at positions 3 and 4 respectively.
A phosphate ion that is the conjugate base of hydrogenphosphate.
Any of a group of glycosaminoglycans with repeating units consisting of variously sulfated beta1->4-linked L-iduronyl-(alpha1->3)-N-acetyl-D-galactosamine units.

A compound having the structure RC#N; thus a C-substituted derivative of hydrocyanic acid, HC#N. In systematic nomenclature, the suffix nitrile denotes the triply bound #N atom, not the carbon atom attached to it.
A gluconate having D-configuration.
A glycosylfructose that is D-fructofuranose attached to a alpha-D-glucopyranosyl unit at position 6 via a glycosidic linkage. It is found in honey and sugarcane.
A phenylethylamine having the phenyl substituent at the 2-position.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of phenylacetic acid.
